</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>A/HRC/27/53/Add.1 
</b></p>
<p><b>2</b>  
</p>
<p>not only guidance but is a yardstick for measuring progress in implementation, which will 
also require close cooperation with civil society if it is to be complete. 
</p>
<p> Slavery in Mauritania was abolished in 1981, criminalized in 2007 and designated 
as a crime against humanity under the 2012 constitutional reform, which constitutes a 
major achievement for the eradication of slavery practices. This initiative was 
complemented by the Government&#8217;s announcement to establish a dedicated special tribunal 
to prosecute crimes of slavery. Notwithstanding the institutional and legal action taken, 
however, the Special Rapporteur reiterated her concern at the need to implement laws and 
policies fully. With regard to the implementation gap, the Special Rapporteur pointed out 
as examples the low number of prosecutions under the criminalization of slavery act, and 
stressed the need to amend it in order to ensure better protection for victims recognized as 
slaves. 
</p>
<p> The Special Rapporteur remains concerned at the lack of reliable information, which 
is a prerequisite for the efficiency of Government programmes. She also stresses the need 
for the Government to publish in the Mauritania official gazette the anti-slavery 
conventions it has ratified as soon as possible in order to raise awareness that all work 
should be entered into freely and respect the fundamental rights of the human person. 
</p>
<p> </p>

